li.p:
 Is there a solution to the equation
	  A\xvec=\bvec where A and \bvec are such
	  that 

	    \begin{bmatrix}
	    1 \amp 2 \\
	    2 \amp 5 \\
	    -1 \amp 0 \\
	    \end{bmatrix}
	    \xvec = \threevec5{-3}{-1}\text{.}

subsection.p:
In the example above, we call the data points (x_i, y_i) and construct the matrix A and vector \bvec as
A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp x_1 \\ 1 \amp x_2 \\ 1 \amp x_3 \\ \end{bmatrix},\hspace{24pt} \bvec = \threevec{y_1}{y_2}{y_3}\text{.}
If we represent a line using the vector \xvec = \twovec bm, the equation A\xvec=\bvec seeks a line that passes through all the data points. In our example, it is clear that there is no such line, a fact reflected by the inconsistency of the equation A\xvec=\bvec.

Instead, we seek \xvec so that A\xvec = \threevec{b+mx_1}{b+mx_2}{b+mx_3} is as close to \bvec as possible. We therefore look at the square of the distance between A\xvec and \bvec:
\begin{aligned} \len{\bvec - A\xvec}^2 \amp = \\ \amp \left(y_1-(b+mx_1)\right)^2 + \left(y_2-(b+mx_2)\right)^2 + \left(y_3-(b+mx_3)\right)^2\text{,} \\ \end{aligned}
and ask to find the values for b and m that make this sum of squares as small as possible. This is why we call this a least squares problem.

Let's now remember how orthogonal projection works: the orthogonal projection \widehat\bvec of \bvec onto the column space \col(A) is defined so that \widehat\bvec - \bvec is orthogonal to \col(A). In other words, \bhat-\bvec is in the orthogonal complement \col(A)^\perp. Remember also that \col(A)^\perp = \nul(A^T), which implies that
A^T(\widehat\bvec-\bvec) = \zerovec\text{.}
Finally, the least squares approximate solution is the vector \xhat such that A\xhat = \widehat\bvec, which gives
\begin{aligned} A^T(A\xhat - \bvec) \amp = \zerovec \\ A^TA\xhat - A^T\bvec \amp = \zerovec \\ A^TA\xhat \amp = A^T\bvec\text{.} \end{aligned}
This is an important equation so we will take note of it here.

Moreover, if the columns of A are linearly independent, there is exactly one solution to the normal equations. To see why, let's imagine, for the moment, that \xvec is a solution to the homogeneous equation A^TA\xvec = \zerovec. Then we have
\begin{aligned} \xvec\cdot(A^TA\xvec) \amp = \xvec\cdot\zerovec = 0 \\ \xvec^TA^TA\xvec \amp = 0 \\ (A\xvec)^T(A\xvec) \amp = 0 \\ (A\xvec)\cdot(A\xvec) \amp = 0 \\ \len{A\xvec}^2 \amp = 0 \\ A\xvec \amp = \zerovec \text{.} \\ \end{aligned}
In other words, if \xvec is a solution to the homogeneous equation A^TA\xvec = \zerovec, then we know that A\xvec = \zerovec. Since we are assuming that the columns of A are linearly independent, we know that the homogeneous equation A\xvec=\zerovec has only the trivial solution \xvec = \zerovec. Therefore, the homogeneous equation A^TA\xvec=\zerovec has only the trivial solution, which means that A^TA has a pivot position in every column. Hence, the normal equations A^TA\xhat = A^T\bvec must have a unique solution.

activity.p:
The rate at which a cricket chirps is related to the outdoor temperature. Here is some data measured experimentally. The chirp rate C is expressed in chirps per second while the temperature T is in degrees Fahrenheit.
\begin{aligned} \amp \begin{array}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline C \amp 20.0 \amp 16.0 \amp 19.8 \amp 18.4 \amp 17.1 \amp 15.5 \amp 14.7 \amp 15.7 \\ \hline T \amp 88.6 \amp 71.6 \amp 93.3 \amp 84.3 \amp 80.6 \amp 75.2 \amp 69.7 \amp 71.6 \\ \hline \end{array} \\ \amp \begin{array}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline C \amp 15.4 \amp 16.3 \amp 15.0 \amp 17.2 \amp 16.0 \amp 17.0 \amp 14.4 \\ \hline T \amp 69.4 \amp 83.3 \amp 79.6 \amp 82.6 \amp 80.6 \amp 83.5 \amp 76.3 \\ \hline \end{array} \end{aligned}
The data is also represented graphically in

subsection.p:
Suppose we have A=QR, and we would like to find the
   least squares approximate solution \xhat of
   A\xvec=\bvec.  Our first step is to project \bvec
   orthogonally onto \col(A) to obtain QQ^T\bvec.  The
   least square approximate solution is then

     \begin{aligned}
     A\xhat \amp = QQ^T\bvec\\
     QR\xhat \amp = QQ^T\bvec\text{.}
     \end{aligned}

   If we multiply both sides of this expression by Q^T and
   remember that Q^TQ=I, the identity matrix, we
   have

     \begin{aligned}
     Q^TQR\xhat \amp = Q^TQQ^T\bvec \\
     IR\xhat \amp = IQ^T\bvec \\
     R\xhat \amp = Q^T\bvec\text{.}
     \end{aligned}

   This is convenient because, as we recall, R is an upper
   triangular matrix so that the equation R\xhat = Q^T\bvec
   can be efficiently solved using back substitution.
